<div id="review_2365679764" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2365679764" />
    <a title="Mehrsa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1045774-mehrsa"><img alt="Mehrsa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1218672696p2/1045774.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2365679764?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mehrsa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mehrsa" href="/user/show/1045774-mehrsa">Mehrsa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2365679764" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3409469487456798938">Comey is an old-school &quot;upstanding guy&quot; and by the end of the book, he is eminently likable and trustworthy. I 100% believe him that he was just trying to do the right thing with the Clinton email investigation, but let&apos;s just say that mistakes were made. He&apos;s honest that he probably thought she would win. But he definitely also reveals that he was suspicious of her and the whole Clinton enterprise. He probably had reason to be. He does note the lone woman at the table during the FBI meetings wh</span>
  <span id="freeText3409469487456798938" style="display:none">Comey is an old-school "upstanding guy" and by the end of the book, he is eminently likable and trustworthy. I 100% believe him that he was just trying to do the right thing with the Clinton email investigation, but let's just say that mistakes were made. He's honest that he probably thought she would win. But he definitely also reveals that he was suspicious of her and the whole Clinton enterprise. He probably had reason to be. He does note the lone woman at the table during the FBI meetings who was like "umm...what if you swing the election to Trump?" Nah. <br /><br />Here are a few other takeaways: <br />1. Comey does not seem to understand Black Lives Matter still and doesn't like the term "mass incarceration. Hmmm. <br />2. Comey did try to diversify the FBI while he was there.<br />3. Martha Stewart should not have lied to Comey. <br /><br />Also some reflections on famous people (which is why we came here, Comey, skip the stories about your childhood): <br />1. Obama is funny and awesome, but a little cocky (duh)<br />2. Bush is funny, but a little mean (again, duh)<br />3. The pee pee tapes are probably real (yikes)<br />4. Trump cannot listen to other people or laugh. <br /><br />If Comey thinks he's ever going win an elected office, he's wrong. I think he's sufficiently pissed off every single political party at this point.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3409469487456798938" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


